me of a major Norman family after the Conquest. In Ireland, this name has been Gaelicized as <b>Bharain</b>.","Irish: adopted as an English form of Gaelic <b>Ó Murnáin</b> (see   Murnane  ,   Warner  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Warrens","meanings":["English: variant of   Warren   with genitival or excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Warrener","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): occupational name from Old French <i>warrennier</i> ‘warrener’, an officer employed to watch over game in a park or game preserve. Compare   Warren  ."]},{"name":"Murnane","meanings":["Irish (Munster): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Murnáin</b>, a shortened and dissimilated form of <b>Ó Manannáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Manannán</i>’, name borne in Celtic mythology by a sea god associated with the Isle of Man. All three syllables appear in the variant <b>Marrinan</b>. This name has also been Anglicized as   Warren   and   Warner  ."]},{"name":"Waren","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Warren  ."]},{"name":"Warne","meanings":["shortened form of   Warren  .","occasionally a habitational name from Wearne in Somerset. The place takes its name from a lost stream-name based on British <i>verno-</i> ‘alder, swamp’.","English:"]},{"name":"Waring","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): variant of   Warren  , from the Norman personal name <i>Warin</i>, derived from ancient Germanic <i>Warino</i>, a short form of various compound names based on the element <i>warin</i> ‘protection, shelter’ or ‘guard’. The name was popular in France and among the Normans (see   Guerin  )."]}]},{"name":"Cecilia","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."],"variants":[{"name":"Cecelia","meanings":["From the Latin name <i>Caecilia</i>, feminine form of <i>Caecilius</i> (  see  Cecil  ). This was a good deal more common than the masculine form, largely due to the fame of the 2nd- or 3rd-century virgin martyr whose name is still mentioned daily in the Roman Catholic Canon of the Mass. She is regarded as the patron saint of music and has inspired works such as  Purcell's  ‘Ode on St Cecilia's Day’, although the reasons for this association are not clear."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":32,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Cecilia Warren was born about 1350, in Blore, Staffordshire, England. She married John de Beresford from 1370 to 1380, in Derbyshire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died after 1408, in England."},"et":{"about 1350–after 1408":"umbes 1350–pärast 1408","1350–1411":"1350–1411","1370–Male":"1370–Surnud","1380–1473":"1380–1473","1390–1475":"1390–1475","1350–1408":"1350–1408","about 1380":"umbes 1380","1473":"1473","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","1370 to 1380":"1370 kuni 1380","1411":"1411","1475":"1475","after 1408":"pärast 1408","1408":"1408","about 1350":"umbes 1350","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","Strafford":"Strafford, New Hampshire, Ameerika Ühendriigid","Beresford, Derbyshire, , Englan